@SquawkCNBC I would ask every guest, including the Citigroup strategist: * What was your S&P 2019 EPS est a year ago? * Why are valuations reasonable since all of the 2019 gains were valuation based? * What is your S&P 2020 EPS est today? * What is your level of confidence?
They are surprises and not predictions. Events that the consensus believes has a less than 20% chance of occurring but I believe is in excess of 50%...... In betting parlance, overlays.
In an endeavour to have respectful debate on the market, sectors and individual stocks.

@realmoney My 15 Surprises for 2020 coming up this morning. Summary: * In 2019 equities rose far faster and interest rates fell sharper than the consensus expected * 2020 could be a year of out-of-the-Vix thinking and mean reversion in valuations/stock prices as profits,

politics, geopolitical events and other uncertainties weigh on global markets * The S&P Index peaks in the month of January - at far lower levels than consensus (sell side) year-end consensus price targets * The year's high in the S&P Index is made in the first month of the year

(at under 3350), the 2020 low in the S&P Index is 2550 and the close is about 2700. * The S&P Index declines by -17% in 2020 * Interest rates rise in 2020 * U.S. energy stocks climb by +20% this year * European bank stocks are a high note - advancing by +30% to +40%
